section.p:
The exterior derivative raises degree by one:

  0\text{-forms}
  \xrightarrow{\ d\ }
  1\text{-forms}
  \xrightarrow{\ d\ }
  2\text{-forms}
  \xrightarrow{\ d\ }
  3\text{-forms}.

The next fact is one of the cleanest in the whole subject:
\boxed{ d^2=0. }
It says that if a form is already an exterior derivative, then taking one more exterior
derivative gives zero.

statement.p:
Define
g(x,y)= \begin{cases} \dfrac{xy(x^2-y^2)}{x^2+y^2}, \amp (x,y)\ne(0,0),\\[2mm] 0, \amp (x,y)=(0,0). \end{cases}
This function has second mixed partial derivatives at the origin, but they are not equal.

First compute g_x(0,y). For y\ne0,

  g_x(0,y) \amp= \lim_{h\to0} \frac{g(h,y)-g(0,y)}{h}
  \amp= \lim_{h\to0} y\frac{h^2-y^2}{h^2+y^2}
  \amp= -y.

Also g_x(0,0)=0. Therefore
g_{xy}(0,0) = \lim_{y\to0}\frac{g_x(0,y)-g_x(0,0)}{y} = \lim_{y\to0}\frac{-y}{y} = -1.

Now compute g_y(x,0). For x\ne0,

  g_y(x,0) \amp= \lim_{h\to0} \frac{g(x,h)-g(x,0)}{h}
  \amp= \lim_{h\to0} x\frac{x^2-h^2}{x^2+h^2}
  \amp= x.

Also g_y(0,0)=0. Therefore
g_{yx}(0,0) = \lim_{x\to0}\frac{g_y(x,0)-g_y(0,0)}{x} = 1.
So
\boxed{ g_{xy}(0,0)=-1, \qquad g_{yx}(0,0)=1. }

subsection.p:
For a function f(x,y,z), the differential is df=f_x\,dx+f_y\,dy+f_z\,dz. This is the work 1-form associated with the gradient vector field 
abla f=(f_x,f_y,f_z). From , the exterior derivative of a work form is the flux form of the curl: d(df)=\Phi_{
abla	imes
abla f}. But d(df)=0. Therefore  oxed{ 
abla	imes(
abla f)=\mathbf 0 } whenever f has continuous second partial derivatives.

Now translate this into vector notation. If \mathbf F=(P,Q,R) and \omega_{\mathbf F}=P\,dx+Q\,dy+R\,dz, then d\omega_{\mathbf F}=\Phi_{
abla	imes\mathbf F}. Applying d again gives d(d\omega_{\mathbf F}) = d\Phi_{
abla	imes\mathbf F} =  igl(
abla\cdot(
abla	imes\mathbf F) igr) \,dx\wedge dy\wedge dz. But d(d\omega_{\mathbf F})=0. Therefore  oxed{ 
abla\cdot(
abla	imes\mathbf F)=0. }

The algebraic rule
d^2=0
has a geometric twin:
\boxed{ \partial(\partial M)=0. }
In words:
\boxed{ \text{the boundary of a boundary is zero.} }

